This is a known breaking change. Android deprecated `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` (API 30+), and .NET 10 MAUI removed the `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` platform-specific API in favor of **edge-to-edge rendering + WindowInsets**.

Here's the recommended approach for a chat screen:

### 1. Keep `adjustResize` in the manifest (still works at manifest level)

In `Platforms/Android/AndroidManifest.xml`, on your `<activity>`:

```xml
<activity
    ...
    android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize" />
```

### 2. Use WindowInsets to react to the keyboard

Create a platform behavior that adjusts your input bar's bottom padding when the IME (keyboard) appears:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/KeyboardInsetBehavior.cs
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Platform;

namespace YourApp.Platforms.Android;

public static class KeyboardInsetBehavior
{
    public static void Attach(Microsoft.Maui.Controls.Page page)
    {
        page.HandlerChanged += (s, e) =>
        {
            if (page.Handler?.PlatformView is global::Android.Views.View nativeView)
            {
                ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(nativeView, new InsetListener(page));
            }
        };
    }

    private class InsetListener(Microsoft.Maui.Controls.Page page)
        : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(
            global::Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Use whichever is larger: keyboard or nav bar
            double bottomPx = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);
            double bottomDp = bottomPx / v.Resources!.DisplayMetrics!.Density;

            page.Padding = new Thickness(0, 0, 0, bottomDp);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

### 3. Wire it up in your chat page

```csharp
public partial class ChatPage : ContentPage
{
    public ChatPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

#if ANDROID
        Platforms.Android.KeyboardInsetBehavior.Attach(this);
#endif
    }
}
```

### 4. Layout your chat screen normally

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="YourApp.ChatPage">
    <Grid RowDefinitions="*,Auto">
        <!-- Messages -->
        <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}"
                        ItemsUpdatingScrollMode="KeepLastItemInView" />

        <!-- Input bar -->
        <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1" Padding="8">
            <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
            <Button Text="Send" Command="{Binding SendCommand}" />
        </HorizontalStackLayout>
    </Grid>
</ContentPage>
```

**How it works:** Instead of the old resize mode shrinking the window, the `WindowInsetsCompat` listener detects the keyboard (IME) height in real time and applies matching bottom padding to the page, pushing your input bar above the keyboard.

**iOS note:** On iOS this isn't needed — `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` (enabled by default in MAUI) handles it. If you ever need to disable it for a specific page, use `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Disconnect(handler)`.
